# Enum Storage Convention

Store .NET enum values as `NVARCHAR(50)` string names, not integer ordinals. The column is named after the concept it represents — no `Id` suffix.

## Why strings

Integer storage couples the database to the declaration order of your enum. Adding a value in the middle, reordering, or removing a deprecated value silently corrupts every existing row. String names are self-describing, survive refactoring, and make SQL queries readable without a lookup table.

## SQL column

```sql
ALTER TABLE [Order]
ADD [Status] NVARCHAR(50) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Created';
```

Not `StatusId INT`, not `StatusCode INT`. Just `Status` as a readable string.

## Writing in C#

```csharp
var parameters = new { Status = order.Status.ToString() };
await connection.ExecuteAsync(
    "UPDATE [Order] SET Status = @Status WHERE Id = @Id", parameters);
```

## Reading in C#

```csharp
var row = await connection.QuerySingleOrDefaultAsync<dynamic>(
    "SELECT Id, Status FROM [Order] WHERE Id = @Id", new { Id = id });

var status = Enum.Parse<OrderStatus>(row.Status);
```

## Trade-off

String storage uses slightly more space than an int and cannot be indexed as efficiently for very high-volume filtering. For the vast majority of use cases, the safety and readability outweigh the marginal performance cost. If you hit a case where enum column performance is measurably critical, document it in an ADR before switching to integer storage.
